{{IPAblink|p}} and {{IPAblink|b}} are reported to be in [[free variation]], although reports of {{IPA|[b]}} could be a misinterpretation of unaspirated {{IPA|[p]}} by English speakers.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz |1994|p=82}}</ref>

There is basic free variation of {{IPAblink|t}} and {{IPAblink|k}}. However, since Hawaiian has no [[affricate consonant|affricates]], no fricative besides {{IPAslink|h}}, and no other stops besides {{IPAslink|p}} and {{IPAslink|ʔ}}, any non-labial and non-glottal stop, fricative, or affricate, can function as a {{IPA|/k/}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz |1994|p=115}}</ref> In essence, {{IPAblink|d}}, {{IPAblink|s}}, {{IPAblink|z}}, {{IPAblink|ts}}, {{IPAblink|dz}}, {{IPAblink|c}}, {{IPAblink|ɟ}}, {{IPAblink|ʃ}}, {{IPAblink|ʒ}}, {{IPAblink|tʃ}}, {{IPAblink|dʒ}}, {{IPAblink|ɡ}}, {{IPAblink|x}}, {{IPAblink|ɣ}} can all "work" as an allophone of {{IPA|/k/}}. Nevertheless, the main allophones noted by the missionaries in the 1820s, and by linguists, are {{IPA|[t]}} and {{IPA|[k]}}. Elbert & Pukui<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1979|pp=26–27}}</ref> point out some instances of a {{IPAblink|ʔ}} allophone. Schütz<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz|1994|pp=77, 79, 116}}</ref> conjectured that a ''t''-dialect existed in the northwestern islands, and a ''k''-dialect in the southeastern islands. Roberts documented a sound between that of English {{angbr|th}} {{IPAblink|θ}} and {{IPAblink|k}} in free variation with {{IPA|[k]}} among elders from O{{okina}}ahu and Kaua{{okina}}i.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Roberts|1967|p=72}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=May 2011}}{{clarify|date=May 2011}}

There is some evidence for instances of free variation between {{IPAblink|n}} and {{IPAblink|ŋ}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz |1994|pp=63–64}}</ref>

There is also free variation between {{IPAblink|l}} ([[lateral consonant|lateral]]), {{IPAblink|ɾ}} ([[tap consonant|tap]]), and {{IPAblink|ɹ}} ([[approximant consonant|approximant]]). Elbert & Pukui<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui |1979|pp=25–26}}</ref> have pointed out some instances of {{IPAblink|n}} and {{IPAblink|ʔ}} as allophones. Schütz<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz |1994|pp=59, 63, 116}}</ref> has conjectured that {{IPA|[ɾ]}} is prevalent in the northwestern islands and {{IPA|[l]}} is prevalent in the southeastern islands.

There is [[free variation]] of {{IPAblink|w}} and {{IPAblink|v}}. {{Harvcoltxt|Pukui| Elbert|1986|p=xvii}} have conjectured that there is [[complementary distribution|conditioned variation]] of {{IPA|[w]}} and {{IPA|[v]}}, but their use of "usually" makes their theory an admission of free variation. Schütz<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Schütz |1994|pp=119–122}}</ref> has conjectured that there was neither {{IPA|[w]}} nor {{IPA|[v]}}, but rather "something between the two". This is most likely {{IPAblink|ʋ}}, a [[labiodental approximant]] (see also Schütz's (1994:113) quotes from letter of Artemas Bishop).

Carter<ref name="Carter1996" /> has shown instances of [[descriptive linguistics|synchronic]] [[alternation (linguistics)|alternation]] of every non-glottal Hawaiian consonant {{IPA|/p, k, m, n, l, w/}} with glottal fricative {{IPAslink|h}} and glottal stop {{IPAslink|ʔ}}. (See [[Hawaiian phonology#Glottal stop]])

There are also instances of variation with zero allophones. For example: {{IPA|/huli/ ⁓ /hui/}} ('turn');<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1986|p=86}}</ref> {{IPA|/luhia/ ⁓ /luia/}} ('variety of shark').<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1986|p=214}}</ref>

=== Glottal stop ===
In Hawaiian, a phonemic glottal stop historically derives from an earlier consonant. A number of words have variant pronunciations between glottal (that is, both {{IPAslink|h}} and {{IPAslink|ʔ}}) and non-glottal consonants; it is conjectured that the forms with a non-glottal consonant are older and that this phenomenon is part of a process of consonant deletion.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Carter |1996|p=373}}</ref>

This can still be seen in the historical development of the dual personal pronouns.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1979|pp=107–108}}</ref><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1986|pp=213, 361}}</ref> This is exhibited in the suffixes for dual and plural number, which come from ''lua'' ('two') and ''kolu'' ('three') respectively.<ref name="Harvcoltxt|Lyovin |1997|p=268">{{Harvcoltxt|Lyovin |1997|p=268}}</ref>

