The {{IPA|/l/}} of {{IPA|/-lua/}} in the first and third person forms has "died" or "vanished", resulting in the modern forms ''māua'', ''kāua'', and ''lāua''. The presence of the glottal stop marks the absence of a "phonetically fuller" consonant. The second person form, ''{{okina}}olua'', contains a glottal stop, implying that the {{IPA|/l/}} used to be there and {{IPA|/ʔ/}} still exists in place of {{IPA|/l/}} in the intermediate forms, {{IPA|/maː + ʔua/}}, {{IPA|/kaː + ʔua/}}, and {{IPA|/laː + ʔua/}}.

A Hawaiian glottal stop thus represents the maximal phonetic reduction of other consonants in centuries past.

Elbert & Pukui<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1979|pp=12, 26–27}}</ref> have shown instances of {{IPA|k ⁓ ʔ}}, and {{IPA|l ⁓ ʔ}}, such as ''mukumuku ⁓ mu{{okina}}umu{{okina}}u'' ('cut'), and ''pūliki ⁓ pū{{okina}}iki'' ('embrace'). Carter (1996:373–374) has shown examples of all seven of the (other) Hawaiian consonants alternating synchronically with glottal stop:

