Vowel quality is the same for long and short vowels, except for {{IPA|/eː/}} vs. {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, and {{IPA|/aː/}} vs. {{IPA|/ɐ/}}:

* When short {{IPAslink|e}} is stressed it is lowered to {{IPAblink|ɛ}}. In a sequence of two or more syllables with {{IPA|/e/}}, unstressed {{IPA|/e/}} can also be lowered to {{IPA|[ɛ]}} but it is otherwise {{IPA|[e]}}. For example, ''{{okina}}ele{{okina}}ele'' ('black') is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈʔɛlɛ.ʔɛlɛ]}}. But ''{{okina}}ale{{okina}}ale'' ('full') is pronounced {{IPA|[ˈʔɐleʔɐle]}}. There are also instances where unstressed short {{IPA|/e/}} can be raised to {{IPA|[i]}}. For example, the negating form, {{IPA|/ʔaʔole/}} or {{IPA|/ʔaʔohe/}}, can be pronounced {{IPA|[ʔaˈʔoli]}} or {{IPA|[ʔaˈʔohi]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1979|p=24}}</ref>
* Short {{IPAslink|a}} is phonetically {{IPAblink|ɐ}} when stressed and {{IPAblink|ə}} when unstressed.

One might argue for free variation of {{IPA|[a]}} and {{IPA|[ɐ]}} for stressed short {{IPA|/a/}}. However, {{Harvcoltxt|Elbert|Pukui|1979|pp=22–24}} have made citations to Kinney (1956) and Newbrand (1951), based on tape-recorded evidence, which specifically noted {{IPA|[ɐ]}}, but not {{IPA|[a]}}. Even so, the pronunciations {{IPA|[ʔaˈʔoli]}} and {{IPA|[ʔaˈʔohi]}} exhibited above, show that there are at least a couple of forms where {{IPA|/a/}} is realized as {{IPA|[a]}}.

