==Home size== {{Globalize|date=July 2018}} According to data from the U.S. Census and Bureau of Labor Statistics found the average floor area of a home in the [[United States]] has steadily increased over the past one hundred years, with an estimated 18.5 square foot increase in the average floor area per year. In 1920, the average floor area was {{convert|1048|sqft|m2}}, which rose to {{convert|1500|sqft|m2}} by 1970 and today sits at around {{convert|2657|sqft|m2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://supplychenmanagement.com/2018/07/15/average-house-size/ |title=How Has the Average House Size Changed? |work=Supply Chen Management |accessdate=2018-07-17 }}</ref>
==Criticism== Some have criticized the house-building industry. Mass house-builders can be risk averse, preferring cost-efficient building methods rather than adopting new technologies for improved building performance.<ref name="Suburban paradigm">{{cite news |last=Arieff |first=Allison |title=Shifting the Suburban Paradigm |work=The New York Times |date=October 2, 2011 |url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/02/shifting-the-suburban-paradigm/?_r=0 |accessdate=2013-11-03}}</ref> Traditional vernacular building methods that suit local conditions and climates can be dispensed with in favour of a generic 'cookie cutter' housing type.<ref name="Suburban paradigm" />
